    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-02-05T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-02-05T05:00:00-05:00" n="59"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d59">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751G.92/237: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Thailand</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grant</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bangkok</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-02-05T17:00:00+07:00"
                            >February 5, 1941—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 6—5:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>66. My telegram No. 61 [<hi rend="italic">62</hi>], February 3, 4 p.m.<note
                        n="79" xml:id="d59fn1">Not printed.</note> The British Minister informed me
                    today that he had followed up his verbal message to the Prime Minister with a
                    note in which he expressed British opposition to any military alliance between
                    Thailand and Japan; to the establishment of any Japanese military or air bases
                    in Thailand; and to any agreement between Thailand and Japan providing for an
                    economic <hi rend="italic">rapprochement</hi> with Japan.</p>
                <p>The British Minister expressed the opinion that the inclusion in the Thailandese
                    delegation to Tokyo of Naivanich Panananda, Director General of the Department
                    of Commerce, who is known to be very pro-Japanese, is indicative of the
                    possibility of an agreement between Thailand and Japan at Tokyo to provide for
                    far reaching economic concessions to Japan.</p>
                <p>Sent to Cavite for repetition to the Department and to Shanghai. Shanghai please
                    repeat to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grant</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
